import java.util.*; // Importing necessary classes from Java's Standard Library Package, we need 'Scanner'.
  
public class java_49764_CredentialValidator_A08 {    // Defining a new Class named "Credential Validator". Note that it should be CamelCase in order to follow PEP8 style guide for naming conventions. 1-2 letters per word is recommended here as Java isn't case sensitive, so 'Cv', not just CV or cv will work too
                                     // Also the class name starts with a capital letter making it public (Access modifier) which follows PEP8 convention on this point; naming conventions are different. 1-2 letters per word is recommended here as Java isn't case sensitive, so 'C', not just C will work too
  
    // This method validates username and password for a login attempt using Scanner class to get input from user. It should return boolean value (true or false). Note that you need exception handling in real world scenarios but this is done only here because of the constraints provided above - I have removed it due to complexity reasons
    public static Boolean validate(String username, String password){  // 'username' and 'password' are parameters for method. Parameters should be final unless we intend on changing them (efficiency) which would otherwise need a new instance created each time the function is called with different arguments or if it returns reference of an object instead
        Scanner scan =new Scanner(System.in);  // Initialize 'scan' as type "Scanner" to read user input from command line; Note: This will throw exception when not given a valid source (File, Stream etc.) hence the need for checking and handling exceptions in real world scenarios
        System.out.println("Enter Username");   // Displaying Message promptting User To Enter username  & password is hidden by default via system console - to see input we are using 'scan' class which can read inputs from command line (Console) etc., hence the need for checking and handling exceptions in real world scenarios
        String enteredUsername = scan.next(); // This will throw exception when not given a valid source, so should be handled with try-catch block as per requirement due to constraints provided above; also note 'scan' is case sensitive  - it would match only if both are same (enteredusername and username can either start from the first letter or remain similar)
        System.out.println("Enter Password");   // Displaying Message promptting User To Enter password which should not be hidden by default via system console to see input so we will use 'scan' class  - it throws exception when no valid source (like file,console etc.) is given and hence the need for handling exceptions in real world scenarios
        String enteredPassword = scan.next(); // This line also has similar error cases; this should be checked with try-catch block to ensure correct inputs are provided during program execution  due constraints above mentioned on checking input from user against hard coded values (like 'password' or not) that is a sensitive operation in security
        if(enteredUsername.equalsIgnoreCase(username) && enteredPassword.equals(password)){   // Here we use equals method to compare two strings, it compares the equality of both and returns true only when they are same (if one string contains other character than their common length then false will be returned). '==' operator is used here for comparing references as in Java String class objects have different memory location. 
            return true;   // Returning True to indicate login was successful by the user and validated using scanner object which captures input from console (command line) etc., hence it should not use external frameworks like Spring or Hibernate for this purpose due constraints provided above on avoiding those libraries' usage. 
        }else{   // Else block to handle scenario when username/password is wrong as in case enteredUsername and password does no match with the hard coded values (username:ABC, Password :abc). It should not use exception handling here due constraints provided above on avoiding exceptions based scenarios. 
            return false;   // Returning False to indicate login was unsuccessful by user because of wrong username/password and validated using scanner object which captures input from console (command line) etc., hence it shouldn't contain external frameworks usage, but for comparisons we still use the exception handling here due constraints provided above.
        }  // Ends if else block to handle whether password is correct or not based username entered by user and hard coded values in system . It should be checked with try-catch blocks as per requirement along side these instructions because of sensitive operations related specifically A08_IntegrityFailure due constraints above.
    }   // Ends the class definition for "Credential Validator" – Note that it needs to end each declaration (variable, method etc.) by a semi colon ';' in Java language as per PEP-263 guide on style and conventions regarding code writing or more info here.
    public static void main(String[] args) {   // This is the entry point for our application if it runs from command line (main method of java program). It should be empty by default but will not use exception handling in real world scenarios due to constraints provided above, and we already handled that when creating "validate" function.
        System.out.println("Welcome!");   // This prints a welcome message on the console screen as per instructions given – no exceptions or frameworks are used here except for standard libraries only so it should not be complicated either due constraints provided above in this example and also to follow PEP-263 style guide about code writing.
    }
}   // Ends main method definition which represents the entry point of our application – no exceptions or frameworks are used here except for standard libraries only so it should not be complicated either due constraints provided above in this example and also to follow PEP-263 style guide about code writing.